# GrabPay One-time Payments<br/> API Reference Guide

# Introduction


1. Fulfil the [Partner Requirements](#partner-requirements) and [Security Recommendations](#security-recommendations).
2. Create your GrabPay partner account to receive your set of dedicated credentials.
3. Invoke the authentication flow.
  - Discover API endpoints (/token and /authorize) dynamically.
  - Generate token using OAuth 2.0 protocol. Later use it to generate HMAC signatures.
4. Enable the One Time Charge payment and refunds flows using APIs.
5. Enable notifications.

You are not required to set up a payment screen to execute payments. However, if you are operating on mobile application, please ensure that your app can handle deep links into the Grab app. The integration process enables you to initiate payments directly from the web browser, Android or iOS apps. The user will authorise the payment in the Grab app, and you will be notified of this authorisation.
This guide explains how to set up the end-to-end payment flow, from initialising to capturing the payment. It also explains how to generate the HMAC signature and the OAuth tokens necessary to authorize the API calls. Follow the instructions in this guide to successfully integrate your app or website with GrabPay.

## Limitations
- The process to set up your account with GrabPay is manual. You must contact the GrabPay team for information required for your initial setup.

# Prerequisites

## Partner Requirements

You should fulfill the following requirements to interact with GrabPay APIs:

- Compatibility with OAuth 2.0 protocol and HMAC. GrabPay APIs ​use the OAuth 2.0 protocol and HMAC to authorize calls.
- Partner should use TLSv1.2 or TLSv1.3 for TLS handshake.
- Partner should integrate directly with GrabPay endpoints without the use of an SDK.
- Your application must be able to support deep links.

## Security Recommendations

Follow these minimum guidelines to ensure the privacy and security of all sensitive information, including other privacy and security requirements in accordance with your firm’s policy.

- **Use KMS to store client IDs and secrets:** ​When handling sensitive information such as client_ids and secrets, use a KMS (Key Management Service) solution to store and retrieve data. For example, you can retrieve the values from AWS KMS during application startup and later store them in your app memory.  When handling client_ids and secrets:
  - Do not store them in a flat file (such as a config file).
  - Do not commit it with the source code.
  - Do not use an external caching mechanism, such as Redis, for storage and retrieval.

- **Use an encrypted database to store user's authorization/refresh tokens:** ​Store these tokens in an encrypted database with roles and permissions set using the principle of​ least privilege ​for schemas and tables.

<aside class="notice">
Caution: Do not use client_ids, secrets, or authorization tokens via the end-user app. Use them strictly only in the backend for the backend to backend communication.
</aside>


- **Production Testing Practices**:
  - If there is a need to perform testing in the production environment, ensure that the above-mentioned security recommendations are followed for handling secrets/tokens. Do not use tools like cURL or Postman for testing in the production environment as commands executed through the CLI may get logged in bash history, process list, or central logging systems, and as Postman configurations are often shared with others.
  - If production data is copied over to testing environments, ensure that user tokens are scrubbed.
  - The above recommendations do not apply for testing in the staging environment.

- **General Guidelines**:
  - Server to server calls must take place in your (partner) application backend, and never from the end-user’s app. Handling these calls from the end-user applications may present performance enhancements or other benefits, but it impacts the overall security and hence must be handled only by your (partner) application backend.

<aside class="notice">
Note: In case the secrets are leaked by any means (such as accidental commits into source control, testing tool compromises, etc.), contact your account manager at GrabPay immediately to update the secrets.
</aside>

Before you use GrabPay APIs within your application, you must create a GrabPay partner account. For more information on how to sign up for a GrabPay partner account, visit the [Grab Platform](https://developer.grab.com/) website.

## Credentials

On successful creation of the account, you will receive the following credentials:

- `partner_id` - A unique partner identification number. A partner_id can have one or more OAuth Client apps associated with it (each identified via a unique client_id) and have configuration for the following platforms: iOS, Android, Web. Each partner can have multiple merchants.
- `partner_secret` - Used to generate the HMAC secret.
- `client_id` - A unique client identification number that is created when registering the OAuth app.
- `client_secret` - Client secret to authenticate the client_id. Used to generate the OAuth token.
- `merchant_id` - A unique merchant identifier used by the partner to differentiate between multiple merchants.
- `Phone number/ Staging account/ manually top up` - A set of accounts for testing on the staging server.

## Scopes
Following are the supported GrabPay scopes that you can use while creating tokens to run specific APIs.

- **openid**: This is the base scope that is required for any integration. It includes the service discovery API and authorization API which is used for token exchange.
- **payment.one_time_charge**: Use this scope to run one-time charge APIs. Running the one-time charge flow with this scope, generates a token which you can use to initiate one-time payment. The generated token is valid only for a specific transaction.

You will receive the scopes at the time of onboarding along with partner credentials.

Grab supports the following API environments:

| Environment | URL       |

| Staging | https://partner-api.stg-myteksi.com |
| Production | https://partner-api.grab.com  |

# API Authentication
All GrabPay API requests go through authentication checks. For added security, some APIs need multiple authentication parameters to make a successful API call. GrabPay APIs use the following authentication methods to successfully authenticate API requests:

- HMAC Signature. For more information on how to generate HMAC signatures, see [Generating HMAC Signatures](#generating-hmac-signatures).
- OAuth 2.0 token. See [Get OAuth Token](#get-oauth-token).
- X-GID-AUX-POP HMAC signature. For more information, see  [Generating the HMAC Signature using OAuth Token](#generating-the-hmac-signature-using-oauth-token).

The required authentication parameters must be included in the request header at the time of request. This section lists the authentication parameters and provides code examples on how to generate them.


## Generating HMAC Signatures

Some requests must contain a valid HMAC-SHA256 signature, otherwise GrabPay API rejects the request. A request signature is calculated using your `partner_secret` key, which is a shared secret known only to you and GrabPay. You must use an HMAC-SHA256 algorithm.

> Golang Example

```go
package main

import (
	"crypto/hmac"
	"crypto/sha256"
	"encoding/base64"
	"encoding/json"
	"fmt"
	"strings"
	"time"
)

func ComputeHMAC(date string, partnerID string, partnerSecret string, responseBody []byte) string {
	hash := sha256.New()
	hash.Write(responseBody)
	mdStr := base64.StdEncoding.EncodeToString(hash.Sum(nil))

	request := []string{"POST", "application/json", date, "/grabpay/partner/v2/charge/init", mdStr}
	request1 := strings.Join(request, "\n")
	request2 := []string{request1, "\n"}
	stringToSign := strings.Join(request2, "")

	hmacSignature := computeHmac256(stringToSign, partnerSecret)
	return hmacSignature
}

func gettime_string(timeformat time.Time) string {
	timeFormatted := (timeformat.Format(time.RFC1123))
	return timeFormatted

}

func computeHmac256(message string, secret string) string {
	key := []byte(secret)
	h := hmac.New(sha256.New, key)
	h.Write([]byte(message))
	result := h.Sum(nil)
	return base64.StdEncoding.EncodeToString(result)
}

func main() {
	var body = map[string]interface{}{
		"partnerTxID":      "ORDER123",
		"partnerGroupTxID": "ORDER123",
		"amount":           100,
		"currency":         "SGD",
		"merchantID":       "44e46f25-7787-44ce-b785-cf9f9b95601e",
		"description":      "paysi-agent-partner-v2-otc",
	}

	responseBody, _ := json.Marshal(body)

	hmacSig := ComputeHMAC("Mon, 12 Nov 2018 08:20:55 GMT", "569c95f1-f5e4-4bd9-8dff-541d8f2af81e", "NvPwMZqiUkYyfDwG", responseBody)
	fmt.Printf("HMAC Signature =\n%v\n", string(hmacSig))
}

```

var CryptoJS = require("crypto-js/core");

function getPath(url) {
    var pathRegex = /.+?\:\/\/.+?(\/.+?)(?:#|\?|$)/;
    var result = url.match(pathRegex);
    if(!result){
        pathRegex = /\/.*/;
        result = url.match(pathRegex);

    return result && result.length > 1 ? result[1] : '';
}

function generateHMACSignature(partnerID, partnerSecret,
  requestURL, requestBody, timestamp) {
  var requestPath = getPath(requestURL);
  var hashedPayload =
  CryptoJS.enc.Base64.stringify(CryptoJS.SHA256(requestBody));
  var requestData = [['POST', 'application/json', timestamp, requestPath,
  hashedPayload].join('\n'), '\n'].join('');
  var hmacSignature = CryptoJS.enc.Base64.stringify(CryptoJS.HmacSHA256(requestData,
  partnerSecret));
  return hmacSignature;
}
var requestBody = '{"amount":100,"currency":"SGD","description":"paysi-agent-partner-v2-otc","merchantID":"44e46f25-7787-44ce-b785-cf9f9b95601e","partnerGroupTxID":"ORDER123","partnerTxID":"ORDER123"}';
var hmacSig = generateHMACSignature("569c95f1-f5e4-4bd9-8dff-541d8f2af81e", "NvPwMZqiUkYyfDwG", "https://partner-api.stg-myteksi.com/grabpay/partner/v2/charge/init", requestBody, "Mon, 12 Nov 2018 08:20:55 GMT")

| Parameter | Description       |
| --------- | ---------- |
| partner_secret | A unique secret shared for each partner_id. |


High-level steps to generate an HMAC signature:

- If the request has a body, such as when initialising a charge, the request body must be hashed using the SHA-256 algorithm and represented as a base-64 encoded value. When building the request body to sign, make sure to escape all the quotes. For example, the following table lists the parameters for the ` /init` API endpoint and to build a payload string to hash:

```shell
PayloadtoSign =
'{\"partnerTxID\":\"ORDER123\",\"partnerGroupTxID\":\"ORDER123\",\"amount\":100,\"currency\":\"SGD\",\"merchantID\":\"44e46f25-7787-44ce-b785-cf9f9b95601e\",\"description\":\"paysi-agent-partner-v2-otc\"}'
```

| Parameter  | Type  | Example values|
| -----------| ------|--------------- |
|partnerTxID| string (max length = 32)<br/>Allowed characters:<ul><li>alphanumeric</li><li>dashes</li><li>underscores</li></ul> |"partnerTxID":"ORDER123"|
|partnerGroupTxID| string (max length = 32)<br/>Allowed characters:<ul><li>alphanumeric</li><li>dashes</li><li>underscores</li></ul> |"partnerGroupTxID":"ORDER123"|
|amount| int64 | 100|
|currency| string (enum)| SGD|
|merchantID | string (value provided by Grab) |"merchantID":"44e46f25-7787-44ce-b785-cf9f9b95601e"|
|description| string (max length = 255) |"description": "paysi-agent-partner-v2-otc”|

- Declare which HTTP method to use. For example, `POST`.
- Specify the request content type. For example, `application/json`.
- Generate a GMT date time value. For example: `Mon, 12 Nov 2018 08:20:55 GMT`.
- Define the resources to access in a standardized fashion. This is the part of the address in between http(s):// and the query string. For example: `/grabpay/partner/v2/charge/init`
- To build the string to sign, combine the HTTP method, request content type, date time, request URI, and the payload hash with the newline in between each parameter.

```shell
StringToSign = 'POST' + '\n'+\
 headers['Content-Type'] + '\n'+\
 headers['Date'] + '\n' +\
 '/grabpay/partner/v2/charge/init' + '\n' +\
 payload_hash + '\n' <<from step 1>>
```

- Create a base64 encoded HMAC signature passing the partner secret as the key and the string to sign as the message.
8. Make sure to include the generated HMAC signature along with the partner_id in the Authorization header parameter.
9. You must also include the date in GMT format and the request content type as header parameters. See an example in the code panel.

```shell
 {'Date': 'Mon, 12 Nov 2018 08:20:55 GMT', 'Content-Type':'application/json', 'Authorization':'569c95f1-f5e4-4bd9-8dff-541d8f2af81e:pSK8CLf03MJzmSPmeDyqsrSIuwyy1QvExmxmf3sme4w='}
```

## Commonly used HTTP Request Headers

### Header Description

| Header  | Description      |
| --------- | ---------- |
|Content-Type | The content type of the request body. You must use `application/json` for this header because GrabPay does not currently support other formats.|
|Date | The date and time in GMT format. For example, `Mon, 21 Dec 2020 08:29:58 GMT`.|
|Authorization | Header required for authorization purpose. If you have the access_token, include the bearer token in the Authorization header along with the Bearer authentication scheme. For example, `'Authorization: Bearer {access_token}'`. For some API endpoints, you can use the HMAC signature as the value. For example, `'Authorization:partner_id:hmac_signature'`.|
|X-GID-AUX-POP (Selected API calls) | The HMAC signature computed using the OAuth access token.|


During authorization, you require two kinds of HMAC signatures to call API resources. One signature before you receive the OAuth access token, and the other after. To understand how to generate HMAC signatures, see the [sample code](?golang#generating-hmac-signatures).


## Constructing an API Request
To construct a REST API request, combine these components:

> Example HTTP request headers

```shell
  -H 'Authorization: {{ partner_id:hmac_signature }}' \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  -H 'Date: Fri, 21 Sep 2018 01:57:48 GMT' \
```

> Example JSON request body

```shell
 -d '{ \
 "partnerGroupTxID":"{{ order_id }}", \
 "partnerTxID":"{{ idempotency_key }}", \
 "currency":"SGD", \
 "amount":1, \
 "description":"test charge", \
 "merchantID":"{{ merchant_id }}" \
}'
```

| Component  | Description      |
| --------- | ---------- |
|The HTTP method | All the methods supported by REST API standards. For example: <br/> <ul><li>GET: Requests data from a resource.</li><li>POST: Submits data to a resource to process.</li><li>DELETE: Deletes a resource.</li><ul>|
|The URI to the main resource | Main URI for getting your resource: <br/>Token: `/grabid` <br/ >Payment: `/grabpay/partner`
|The URI to the resource | The resource to query, submit data to, update, or delete. For example: `/v2/charge`|
|Query parameters | Parameters to be sent to the GET endpoint. For example: <br /> `https://<<api-endpoint>>/grabpay/partner/v2`<br/>`/charge/{partnerTxID}/status?currency=SGD`|
|HTTP request headers  | Authorization and HMAC headers. For example: <br /> `-H 'Authorization: {{ partner_id:hmac_signature }}' \` <br /> `-H 'Content-Type: application/json' \`<br />`-H 'Date: Fri, 21 Sep 2018 01:57:48 GMT' \`|
|A JSON request body | Required for most POST, PUT, and PATCH calls. See an example in the code panel. |

# Steps to enable One-time-Payments

Integrating with GrabPay webview to enable one-time payment flow in your application or website is a mix of calling certain APIs and writing code for certain tasks. This includes generating HMAC signatures, X-GID-AUX-POP signatures, Web URLs and creating webhooks.

1. Create a HMAC signature and initiate a one-time payment via `/charge/init`.
2. Generate a Web URL and load the URL on the GrabPay user's browser. The GrabPay user verifies their identity and approves the charge. Consequently, the GrabPay user is redirected to the partner's provided URL.
3. Obtain the codes by one of these two methods:
  - Handle the auth notification when user approves the charge and call `one-one_time_charge/status`.
  - Generate an OAuth token using the code received from the redirected URL.
4. Create a HMAC signature and complete a one-time payment via `/charge/complete`.
5. Check the payment status from our Check Status API.

If this value is provided, the calculated value should match the total amount.</li><li>itemCategory (string - enumerated value): Category list. See the table below for the complete list of categories.</li><li>url (string): The item URL at the merchant site.</li><li>imageURL (string): The URL of the item’s image at the merchant site.</li><li>supplierDetails:<ul><li>supplierID (string): Unique identifier of the supplier.</li><li>supplierName (string): The name of the supplier who is supplying the item.</li><li>supplierURL (string): Supplier’s URL.</li><li>legalID (string): Optional. Supplier’s legal unique identifier.</li><li>supplierPhone (string): Supplier’s email address.</li><li>supplierEmail (string): Supplier’s email address.</li><li>supplierAddress (string): Suppliers office address.</li><li>supplierRating (double) Supplier’s rating.</li></ul></li></ul> |
|shippingDetails | array of object <br/>(max 255 characters<br/> per field)| Optional. Each field can have a maximum of 255 characters. <ul><li>firstName (string): First name of the customer.</li><li>lastName (string): Surname of the customer.</li><li>address (string): Customer’s postal address.</li><li>city (string): Customer’s city name.</li><li>postalCode (string): Customer’s Zip code.</li><li>phone (string): Customer’s phone number.</li><li>email (string): Customer’s email address.</li><li>countryCode (string): Customer’s country code.</li></ul> |

### Response Elements

| Parameter | Type | Description|
| ---------------- | ---------- |---------- |
|partnerTxID | string | Partner transaction ID used as the idempotency key for subsequent API calls.|

### HTTP Response Codes

| HTTP Code |Reason| Action |
| ---------------- | ---------- | ---------- |
| 200 OK |Transaction has been initiated successfully. Grab has received the transaction details and generated a transaction ID for this specific transaction.| - |
| 400 Bad Request |The request payload either has missing or incorrect parameters. Check that all required parameters are being sent, and that all parameters are sent in the correct format.| Fix and retry the operation. |
| 401 Unauthorized |This transaction call is not permitted due to incorrect credentials sent in the request. Possible reasons include an incorrect HMAC signature sent in the headers.| Fix and retry the operation. |
| 403 Forbidden |This transaction call is forbidden.| Fix and retry the operation. |
| 409 Conflict |There are certain conflicts with certain parameters sent in the request with the configuration on our servers. Take a look at the **Reason Codes** section below on the possible list of reasons for the conflict.| Fix and retry the operation. |
| 500 Internal Server Error |There are internal errors occurring in our service, please try the request again later.| Retry the operation at a later time. |

<h3>Reason Codes</h3>

When a non successful HTTP code is returned, a `reason` parameter might also be returned to elaborate on the failure. These are a list of reason codes that might be returned in a non successful HTTP response.

> Sample non successful response with reasons

```shell
{
    "code": 4090,
    "reason": "invalid_merchant"
}
```

| Reason| Description |
| ---------- |---------- |
| currency_mismatch | The currency does not match with the designated currency for your merchant_id.|
| invalid_merchant | The merchant_id passed in the request is not a valid one. Ensure that you pass your assigned merchant_id. If you are still facing issues, please reach out to our support team to retrieve your designated merchant_id for GrabPay transactions.|
| transaction_already_exists | The `partnerTxID` parameter sent in the request already exists in our system. It is important to generate a unique ID everytime a transaction is initialized.|
| client_error | There are some errors in processing this request due to certain parameters sent in the request. |

# Generate Web URL

In this stage, generate a Web URL that provides a web interface for Grab's user-level authentication. This helps the end-user login or register for GrabPay. Ensure that you can generate the HMAC signature and successfully call the `/charge/init` API endpoint before starting this step.

## Web URL Parameters

> Sample javascript to generate Web URL

```javascript
// request param get from Init
function getAuthorizeLink(request) {
	var scope = ['openid', 'payment.one_time_charge'];
	var response_type = 'code';
	var redirect_uri = 'https://yourwebserver/listener'; // Your redirect URL
	// how to generate nonce, state and code_verifier can be seen on other example
	var nonce = generateRandomString(16);
	var state = generateRandomString(7);
	var code_challenge_method = 'S256';
	var code_verifier = generateCodeVerifier(64);
	var code_challenge = generateCodeChallenge(code_verifier);
	var countryCode = "SG";
	var currency = "SGD";
	var params = {
		client_id: client_id,
		scope: scope.join(' '),
		response_type: response_type,
		redirect_uri: redirect_uri,
		nonce: nonce,
		state: state,
		code_challenge_method: code_challenge_method,
		code_challenge: code_challenge,
		request: request,
		acr_values: "consent_ctx:countryCode=" + countryCode + ",currency=" currency
	};
	var str = $.param(params);
	// You should get this URL from service discovery
	var url =
		'https://partner-api.stg-myteksi.com/grabid/v1/oauth2/authorize?' + str;
	return url;
}

function generateRandomString(length) {
	var text = '';
	var possible =
		'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789';
	for (var i = 0; i < length; i++) {
		text += possible.charAt(Math.floor(Math.random() * possible.length));
	}
	return text;
}

function base64URLEncode(str) {
	return str.toString(CryptoJS.enc.Base64).replace(/=/g,
		'').replace(/\+/g, '-').replace(/\//g, '_');
}
var nonce = generateRandomString(16);
var state = generateRandomString(7);
var codeVerifier = base64URLEncode(generateRandomString(64));
var codeChallenge = base64URLEncode(CryptoJS.SHA256(codeVerifier))
```

> Sample URL

```shell
  https://partner-api.stg-myteksi.com/grabid/v1/oauth2/authorize?acr_values=consent_ctx%3AcountryCode%3DSG,currency%3DSGD&client_id={{CLIENT_ID}}&code_challenge=PP2Ut_vyvfkytkYEhobjNvYG7dNxil3vQNROIsm_JMU&code_challenge_method=S256&nonce=zYPZ8hIYT7CEfgCY&redirect_uri=https://www.developer.grab.com&request=eyJhbGciOiAibm9uZSJ9eyJjbGFpbXMiOnsidHJhbnNhY3Rpb24iOnsidHhJRCI6IjNlZmQ1MGI5NmFjMTQ1NViNzczNjU1YTEyMDRhNDNjIn19fQ.&response_type=code&scope=openid%20payment.one_time_charge&state=fdgidgI
```

> Sample Redirect URL

```shell
<<redirect_url>>?code=0865c8ba78c9477b92757ec21b671097&state=z9t0TkP
```


| Parameter | Type | Description|
| ---------------- | ---------- | ---------- |
|acr_values| Enumerated string | **Required**. Currently, supports the value `consent_ctx`. <br/> The OpenID Connect ACR optional parameter to the /authorize endpoint will be utilized to pass in consent_ctx". For example: <br /><br/> `acr_values=consent_ctx:countryCode=SG,currency=SGD` <br /><br />`countryCode`: Specify the two-letter ISO country code of the country where the transaction is initiated. Currently, supports SG, MY, PH and ID. <br /><br />`currency`: Currency that is associated with the payment amount. Specify the three-letter ISO currency code. Currently, supports only SGD, MYR, PHP, and IDR.|
| client_id |string | **Required**. Specify the client_id created during the OAuth registration process.|
| code_challenge | string | **Required.** `code_verifier = random STRING using:[A-Z] / [a-z] / [0-9] / "-" / ` <br/ > `"." / "_" / "~" `[`from Section 2.3 of [RFC3986]`](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3986#section-2.3)`, min length = 43; max length = 128 `<br /> `code_challenge = BASE64URL-ENCODE(SHA256(ASCII(code_verifier)))` <br/> Make sure to cache the `code_verifier` value. You have to specify this value when generating the OAuth token at the `/token` endpoint. For more details and reference example (test values to verify source code implementation), see, [PKCE spec](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7636#appendix-B). |
|code_challenge_method | string | **Required.** Allowed value: S256. S256 is the security baseline in Grab implementation. Defined in [PKCE spec](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7636). Note `plain` specified in this spec is not allowed. |
|nonce |string |**Required. ** Specify a random string. Recommended to use base64 or hex encoded random string. This value is included in the nonce claim in the id_token. The nonce should be compared to the value in id_token, when this token is obtained from the `/token` endpoint. |
|redirect_uri |string| **Required.** Specify the URL where the customer is redirected on successful completion of the payment via GrabPay. Make sure that the client app is registered with this redirect URL. In the end of the authorization code flow, the `/authorize` endpoint redirects here (and the OS handovers the control to the app). Note the un-encoded value used in the example: <br />`gc-0208d86bfe374b8eb6f2c47915b27b29-o6sucaYZ52MN-ios://ouathcallback1` |
|request |string |**Required**. The request is passed as an unsigned base64 encoded JWT. This value is the `request` received in the JSON response of the [/charge/init API](#initiate-payment).|
|response_type |string |**Required**. Currently accepts the value `code`. Specifies the authorization code flow (the pattern to use for third-party mobile client integration) |
|scope |string |**Required**. Scope that will be used in integration process. Currently accepts the value: <br/>`payment.one_time_charge`|
| state |string |**Required**. Specify a random string used to mitigate CSRF attacks. Calling application should compare the value supplied here with the value returned from the final redirect (which also has the state parameter). Recommend using a base64 or hex encoded random string.|



# Receiving and acknowledging the redirect from GrabPay

As users complete the payment on our checkout page, users will be redirected back to the URL as specified in the `redirect_uri` from the [Generate Web URL](#generate-web-url) step.

If the transaction is successful, the URL will contain a `code` in the query parameters. However, if there are issues in the checkout flow, an `error` parameter will be specified in the URL instead.

Regardless of the status of the transaction in the checkout flow, a `state` parameter will also be set in the query parameters. You should also ensure that this state parameter matches the `state` parameter sent to GrabPay at the [Generate Web URL](#generate-web-url) step.

### GrabPay Redirect Error Messages

| Error                  | Reason                                                       |
| ---------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| user_canceled          | The user has requested to cancel the transaction.            |
| session_expired        | The session for this transaction has expired.                |
| invalid_acr_values     | An invalid `acr_values` parameter was passed in the generated Web URL. Please ensure that the `acr_values` query parameter is generated in the correct format. |
| invalid_token          | An invalid `request` object was passed in the generated Web URL. Be sure to only use a request parameter that was returned in a successful [Initiate Payment](#initiate-payment) step. |
| invalid_argument       | There are invalid parameters passed with the generated Web URL. Ensure that all required parameters are sent in the URL in the correct format. |
| invalid_scope          | An invalid `scope` parameter was passed in the generated web URL. Be sure to only use a `scope` parameter as given by the integration team. |
| mfa_not_completed      | The multi-factor authentication step for the user was not successful. |
| transaction_not_found  | A valid transaction could not be located from the specified request. Ensure that all required parameters are sent in the URL, and in the correct format. |
| kyc_compliance_decline | Transaction was unsuccessful due to regulatory compliance checks. |
| transaction_declined   | Transaction was declined.                                    |
| server_error           | Transaction could not be completed due to an internal server issue. Should this error occur again, please reach out to the support team for any updates of system downtime. |
| client_error           | Transaction could not be completed due to an unspecified user error in the checkout flow. |
| insufficient_balance   | Transaction could not be completed due to an insufficient balance on the user's selected payment method. |
| unknown                | Transaction could not be processed in time. As a result, the transaction will be cancelled. Users may still encounter a temporary hold of funds in their wallet. |

# Generating the HMAC Signature using OAuth Token

Before you can run any API endpoints that require X-GID-AUX-POP, you must generate a second HMAC signature using the OAuth token received from the previous step.

<aside class="notice">
 Most of the subsequent API endpoints require you to pass the generated HMAC signature in the request header as `X-GID-AUX-POP`. Make sure to generate them each time you run those endpoints with the access token received from the previous step.
</aside>
## Prerequisites

- Access token from the previous API endpoint.
- Client secret.


## Steps to Generate the Signature

> Sample javascript to generate signature

```javascript
  // Refer the sample code below to get to the HMAC signature after you’ve got your
  // access_token. This signature must then be passed on to the X-GID-AUX-POP header.
  // CalculateHMACForPOP ...
  // "crypto/hmac"
  // "crypto/sha256"
  // "encoding/base64"
  func CalculateHMACForPOP(clientSecret, accessToken string)
	(string, error) {
		// use current timestamp and OAuth2 access token and hash them together
		var unixNow = time.Now().Unix()
		var messageToHash = fmt.Sprintf("%d%s", unixNow, accessToken)
		hash: = hmac.New(sha256.New, [] byte(clientSecret))
		if _, err: = hash.Write([] byte(messageToHash));
		err != nil {
			return "", err
		}
		var signature =
			base64.RawURLEncoding.EncodeToString(hash.Sum(nil))
		// append the signature and time in a JSON format
		jsonPayload: = map[string] interface {} {
			"time_since_epoch": unixNow,
			"sig": signature,
		}
		payloadBytes, err: = grabjson.Marshal(jsonPayload)
		if err != nil {
			return "", err
		}
		// encode the payload to base 64 raw URL string
		var encodedPayload =
			base64.RawURLEncoding.EncodeToString(payloadBytes)
		return encodedPayload, nil
	}
//For information on access to nonce, state, and codeChallenge, see the example below:
	function generateRandomString(length) {
		var text = '';
		var possible = 'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789';
		for (var i = 0; i < length; i++) {
			text += possible.charAt(Math.floor(Math.random() *
				possible.length));
		}
		return text;
	}

function base64URLEncode(str) {
	return str.toString(CryptoJS.enc.Base64).replace(/=/g,'').replace(/\+/g, '-').replace(/\//g, '_');
}
var nonce = generateRandomString(16);
var state = generateRandomString(7);
var codeVerifier = base64URLEncode(generateRandomString(64));
var codeChallenge = base64URLEncode(CryptoJS.SHA256(codeVerifier))

```

> Sample Signature

```shell
eyJ0aW1lX3NpbmNlX2Vwb2NoIjoxNTUxNzc5OTk1LCJzaWciOiJfajh3dm1IT0NXRFdJSGdIVE8yS0tSSkpqVHZRdW9WS2RnWGo4TE1kWm13In0
```

1. Get the current Unix timestamp.
2. Create a string to sign by concatenating the Unix timestamp and the access token received in the previous step.
3. Convert the concatenated string to the JSON format.
4. Create a base64 encoded HMAC signature passing the client secret as the key and the string to sign as the message. See the code panel for a sample javascript code that generates a signature.

# Handle Processing Transaction Status

Certain transactions may take longer to process. If you do not set the `isSync` parameter to `true` while [initiating a payment](#initiate-payment), then the [Confirm Payment](#complete-payment) API response may return an intermediate transaction status value i.e. `processing`, if the transaction is still in process. The `processing` transaction status will turn into one of the final transaction statuses (i.e. `success / failed`) at a later time. Make sure to rely only on the `success` and `failed` as the final transaction statuses.

You can handle the `processing` transaction status in the following ways:

- If your business is not time-sensitive and can afford the transaction processing time, then when receiving an unknown transaction status in [Confirm Payment](#complete-payment) response, wait for the notification call. GrabPay sends the final transaction status via a notification call. Alternatively, you can run the [Check Payment Status](#check-payment-status) endpoint to find the current status of the transaction. However, do not run the API more than once every 2 minutes.

- If your business is time-sensitive and wish to receive an immediate final transaction status from GrabPay, specify `true` in the `isSync` field when [initiating a payment](#initiate-payment). You can expect to receive only `success` or `failed` transaction statuses for a **large majority** of transactions in the [Complete Payment](#complete-payment) response.

- However, in rarer cases you might still receive an `processing` status in the response even if you have specified `true` in the `isSync` field, if the system is temporarily unable to ascertain the final status of a transaction in time. Should this happen, you can run the [Check Payment Status](#check-payment-status) endpoint to find the current status of the transaction. However, do not run the API more than once every 2 minutes.


Once the final status of the transaction is returned from the check status API (i.e. `success / failed`), you may continue with the appropriate adjustments to this transaction if needed (eg: a refund).

- However if you wish to refund the transaction via [Generate Refunds](#generate-refunds), you still need to handle unknown status of the refund API call. The `isSync` attribute is not available for refunds.

# Check Payment Status

There are two endpoints available for checking the payment status of a One Time Payment transaction. One of the status check endpoints is One Time Charge Status endpoint, which authenticated with a HMAC signature, while the other is the Partner Charge Status endpoint, which is authenticated by an OAuth token redeemed from the [Get OAuth Token](#get-oauth-token) step.

There are two main differences of using the One Time Charge status check endpoint over the Partner Status check endpoint.

1) The One Time Charge status check endpoint for a particular transaction can be called at any time, after you have initiated a transaction in the [Initiate Payment](#initiate-payment) step. For the Partner Charge Status endpoint, you need the GrabPay user to have provided consent for the payment, and have redeemed the OAuth access token before having access to the endpoint. Alternatively, the Payment Charge Status endpoint can be called after you have redeemed the OAuth access token. At this point, the user would have already consented to the payment or already authorised the payment.

2) The One Time Charge status check endpoint returns `code` in the response, which can be used to redeem the OAuth token in the [Get OAuth Token](#get-oauth-token) step. The Partner Charge Status endpoint does not offer this feature.

<h3>One Time Charge Status Endpoint</h3>

Check the payment status for **One Time Charge** flows. Make sure to provide the partner transaction ID and currency value that you have provided the in `/charge/init` request. Otherwise, the endpoint returns a `HTTP 404 ` response.


<h5>Alternative way to retrieve the OAuth Token</h5>

This endpoint can also be used in conjunction with the webhook notifications for partners to retrieve the OAuth access token and complete the payment.

When a GrabPay user consents to a payment, the merchants receive a webbook notification of that consent action (txType will be Auth). On receiving the webhook notification for user payment consent, merchants can perform any of these additional actions:
- Call the One Time Charge Status endpoint to retrieve the `OAuthCode` parameter.
- Redeem the OAuth token in [Get OAuth Token](#get-oauth-token).
- Complete the payment in [Complete Payment](#complete-payment).

# Handle Payment Notification
GrabPay will send notification automatically on every transaction status using webhook instead of you running the check status endpoint.

Make sure to verify the validity of the received notification. You can compare the HMAC signature from the Authorization header with the one that you created when generating the charge request.

<aside class="notice">
  Note: The notification output structure from GrabPay might change in the future.
</aside>
<img src="data:image/png;base64,">


### Header Parameters

> Sample Request Sent From Grab

```shell

curl -X POST https://partner-api.stg-myteksi.com \
-H 'Authorization: {{ signed_hmac }}'
-H 'Content-Type: application/json; charset=utf-8' \
-H 'Date: Thu, 13 Sep 2018 08:49:37 GMT' \
-d '{ \
 "txType":"Capture", \
 "partnerTxID":"{{ idempotency_key }}", \
 "txID":"{{ idempotency_key_from_grab }}", \
 "currency":"SGD", \
 "amount":1000, \
 "status":"success", \
 "paymentMethod":"INSTALMENT_4", \
 "createdAt":1516181437, \
 "completedAt":1516181437,\
 "Payload":{} \
}’

```


| Parameter        | Type|  Description |
| ---------------- | ---------- | ---------- |
| Authorization | bearer token | Grab sends Authorization in this format: `partner_id:hmac_signature`.|
| Date | date | The date and time in GMT format. For example, `Mon, 21 Dec 2020 08:29:58 GMT`.|
| Content-Type | string | Grab will send ​`application/json` as​ ​Content-Type. However, when you compute HMAC, use the value `application/json; charset=utf-8​` as Content-Type.|


### Body of the Webhook

> Sample Response

```shell
{
 "txID":"66f3f271cc994f1bb1e46e6fe4fd8727",
 "status":"success",
 "description":""
}
```

| Parameter        | Type|  Description |
| ---------------- | ---------- | ---------- |
| txType | string | Currently supports the transaction types: <br /> <ul><li>`Auth`</li><li>`Capture`</li><li>`Refund`</li><li>`Cancel`</li></ul><br /> In future, this might be updated. |
| partnerTxID | string (max length = 32)<br/>Allowed characters:<ul><li>alphanumeric</li><li>dashes</li><li>underscores</li></ul> | Specify the partner transactionID of the event. |
| txID | string | Specify the GrabPay transactionID, should be a 32-bit UUID formatted string. |
| origTxID | string | Specify a reference transaction ID which traces to the original GrabPay transaction. For example, if it is a refund event, this will be the original charge transaction ID. If it is not related to the original transaction, this should be an empty string. |
| amount | int64 | A positive integer in the smallest currency unit (e.g., 100 cents to charge S$1.00, a zero-decimal currency). For example, S$5.34 will be represented as 534. |
| currency | string |The three-letter ISO currency code. For example: ​`SGD`,` MYR`, `PHP`, and `IDR`.|
| status | string | (deprecated, please use txStatus instead) Specify one of the following values: <br/><ul><li>`"success"`</li><li>`"failed"`</li></ul>|
| paymentMethod | enum | Returns one of the following values: <ul> <li>GPWALLET</li> <li>POSTPAID</li><li>INSTALMENT_4</li></ul>|
| completedAt | int64 | Specify the time when the transaction completed in Unix timestamp format.|
| createdAt | int64 | Specify the transaction creation time in Unix timestamp format. |
| payload | jsonRaw | A JSON format with any additional information. |
| txStatus | string | Refer to the ​[Transaction Status​](#transaction-status) table for a list of all possible transaction statuses and their descriptions.|
| reason | string | The reason code is for additional information on the payment. It is an optional response element. In certain cases, reason code could be empty. For example, when `txStatus​` is ​`success`.</br> Refer to the ​[Reason Cod​e](#reason-codes) table for a list of all possible reason codes and their descriptions.|

# Payload for Webhook
|Parameter| Type | Description |
|------|----------|----------------|
| partnerGroupTxID | string | partnerGroupTxID that was passed to GrabPay during the transaction.|
| paymentMethod | string | Payment method used by User to complete payment in GrabPay.|
| echo | string | Merchant reference passed to GrabPay during the transaction.|
| rewardsMeta | jsonRaw |  Defines  information related to rewards, and this information is sent back only in case of a funded promotion at the merchant's end.|

# rewardsMeta Details
| Parameter     | Type   | Description                                           |
| ------------- | ------ | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| offerCode     | string | Promotional code used in the transaction.             |
| offerName     | string | Name of the promotional code used in the transaction. |
| offerDiscount | int64  | The total user discount offered for the transaction.  |

Note: This information will only be sent in the webhook if the promotional code used in the transaction is from a merchant funded promotion.

# TxType for Webhook

|txType| description|
|------|--------------------------|
| Auth | GrabPay has withheld the transaction amount after the user has consented to make the payment. A success txStatus will be received if the Auth was successful. |
| Capture | GrabPay has captured the Auth amount and has transferred it to the merchant's wallet. |
| Cancel | Auth transaction is being cancelled since the merchant did not capture the Auth amount. |
| Refund | Payment is being refunded. |


Note: Multiple webhook notifications may be sent to the merchant for a unique transaction. However, the txType in the API Response body will vary. For example, in the case of authorization transactions it is `Auth`. For capture transactions, it is `Capture`.

# Transaction Status for Charge

| txStatus               | Description                                                  |
| ---------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| success                | The Initiate payment action ended successfully.              |
| failed                 | The Initiate payment action failed.                          |
| processing             | System is processing this transaction, wait for the webhook notification. Alternatively, you can ​run the check status endpoints to find out the current status of the transaction. However, do not run the API more than once every 2 minutes. |
| cancelled              | Occurs when <br />1) The user did not click Pay <br />2)  `/charge/complete` was not called and the authorization of the transaction had expired. |
| authorised             | Defines the payment transaction as authorized but not completed. |
| authorisation_declined | Defines the payment transaction authorization as declined.   |

# Reason Codes for Charge

These are a list of possible reasons returned the the API response for charge and the status check endpoints. This list might be updated over time. Thus, it is important for your system to handle any unknown reason codes in the response that are not mentioned in this document.

| Reason Code            | Description                                                  |
| ---------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| currency_mismatch      | Currency used in this request does not match with the merchant configuration. |
| no_record_found        | No record found for this transaction.                        |
| authorising            | System is processing a request for the transaction to be authorised. |
| capturing              | System is processing a request for the transaction to be captured. |
| user_fail_consent      | User was not able to provide approval for the transaction in time. |
| pending_user_consent   | Transaction is still pending user's approval on GrabPay's checkout page. |
| pending_capture        | Transaction is still pending a `/charge/complete` call for the payment to be finalized. |
| cancelling             | Transaction is in the process of being cancelled.            |
| auth_expired           | Transaction is cancelled as the transaction was not completed with the `/charge/complete` call in time. |
| unknown                | The charge is still being processed, however the reason for this cannot be determined. |
| kyc_compliance_decline | Transaction was unsuccessful due to regulatory compliance checks. |
| transaction_decline    | Transaction was declined.                                    |
| insufficient_balance   | There was an insufficient balance in the user's wallet to complete the transaction. |

# Generate Refunds

Run the refund API endpoint to generate full or partial refunds for a specific transaction.

## Prerequisites

Make sure you have run the `/charge/complete` API endpoint. You must specify the transaction ID
from that endpoint’s response.

| ---------------- | ---------- |
| ​POST | https://{{api-endpoint}}/grabpay/partner/v2/refund|

| ---------------- | ---------- | ---------- |
| Authorization | bearer token | **Required.** Header required for authorization purpose. Specify the bearer access token in the Authorization header along with the Bearer authentication scheme. For example, `'Authorization: Bearer {access_token}'`.|
| X-GID-AUX-POP  | token | **Required.** The HMAC signature computed using the OAuth access token.|
| Date | date | **Required.** The date and time in GMT format. For example, `Mon, 21 Dec 2020 08:29:58 GMT`. |
| Content-Type  | string | **Required**. The content type of the request body. You must use `application/json` for this header because GrabPay does not currently support other formats.|


## Request Parameters

> Sample API Request

```shell
POST https://partner-api.stg-myteksi.com/grabpay/partner/v2/refund \
-H 'Authorization: Bearer {{ OAuth2_token }}' \
-H 'X-GID-AUX-POP: {{ POP_signature }}'
-H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
-H 'Date: Thu, 13 Sep 2018 08:49:37 GMT' \
-d '{ \
 "partnerGroupTxID":"{{ order id }}", \
 "partnerTxID":"{{ idempotency_key }}", \
 "currency":"SGD", \
 "amount":1000, \
 "description":"test charge", \
 "merchantID":"{{ merchant_id }}", \
 "originTxID":"{{ tx_id for the charge }}" \
}'


```
| Parameter        | Type|  Description |
| ---------------- | ---------- | ---------- |
| partnerGroupTxID | string (max length = 32)<br/>Allowed characters:<ul><li>alphanumeric</li><li>dashes</li><li>underscores</li></ul> | **Required.** ​ Order_id. This is the unique identifier of each transaction generated by the partner. Each transaction might consist of several charges. Usually the value is a single receipt ID from the partner and can be displayed to the user. |
| partnerTxID | string (max length = 32)<br/>Allowed characters:<ul><li>alphanumeric</li><li>dashes</li><li>underscores</li></ul> | **Required.** ​ Specify the partner transaction ID, used as the idempotency key. Make sure to provide the same partner transaction ID used when generating the [signature​](#generating-the-hmac-signature-using-oauth-token). |
| amount | int64 | **Required.** ​ Transaction amount as integer. A positive integer in the smallest currency unit (e.g., 100 cents to charge S$1.00, a zero-decimal currency). For example, S$5.34 is represented as 534. |
| currency | string | **Required.** ​ Currency that is associated with the payment amount. Specify the three-letter ISO currency code. Currently, supports only `SGD`, `MYR`, `PHP`, and `IDR`. |
| description | string | Optional. Description of the charge.|
| merchantID | string |  **Required.** ​ Specify the merchant account to credit to on successful transaction. Each partner can have multiple merchant accounts linked to the partner account. Merchant account is specific to one currency.|
| originTxID | string |  **Required.** ​ The value of ​`TxID​` from the response of the `/charge​` ​endpoint.|

}

| Parameter        | Type|  Description |
| ---------------- | ---------- | ---------- |
| txID | string | A 32-bit UUID format​ted ​GrabPay transaction ID​. |
| status | string | (deprecated, please use txStatus instead) Returns one of the following values: <br /><ul><li>success</li><li>failed</li></ul> |
| paymentMethod | enum | Returns one of the following values: <ul> <li>GPWALLET</li> <li>POSTPAID</li><li>INSTALMENT_4</li></ul>|
| description | string | If the transaction is successful, that is, if the ​`status: success​`, then description will be empty. However, if the transaction failed (i.e. ​`status: failed​`), the API provides a description of the error. For example: `refund_exceeds_charge_amount​`. |
| txStatus | string | Returns one of the following values: <ul><li>`success`</li><li>`failed`</li><li>`processing`</li></ul> Refer to the ​[Transaction Status for Refunds​](#transaction-status-for-refunds) table for a list of all possible transaction statuses and their descriptions. |
| reason | string | The reason code is for additional information on the payment. It is an optional response element. In certain cases, reason code could be empty. For example, when `txStatus​` is ​`success`.</br> Refer to the ​[Reason Cod​es for Refunds](#reason-codes-for-refunds) table for a list of all possible reason codes and their descriptions. |

## HTTP Response Codes

| Code | Reason    | Action          |
| ------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ | ---------------- |
| 200 OK                    | The API request is successfully processed.                   | - |
| 400 Bad Request           | The request payload either has missing or incorrect parameters. Check that all required parameters are being sent, and that all parameters are sent in the correct format. | Fix and retry the operation. |
| 401 Unauthorized          | This transaction call is not permitted due to incorrect credentials sent in the request. Possible reasons include an incorrect bearer token sent in the `Authorization` header. | Fix and retry the operation. |
| 403 Forbidden             | This transaction call is forbidden.                          | Fix and retry the operation. |
| 409 Conflict              | There are certain conflicts with certain parameters sent in the request with the configuration on our servers. Take a look at the **Reason Codes for Refund Errors** section below on the possible list of reasons for the conflict. | Fix and retry the operation. |
| 500 Internal Server Error | There are internal errors occurring in our service, please try the request again later. | Retry the operation at a later time. |



<h3>Reason Codes for Refund Errors</h3>

When a non successful HTTP code is returned, a `reason` parameter might also be returned to elaborate on the failure. These are a list of reason codes that might be returned in a non successful HTTP response

| Reason                           | Description                                                  |
| -------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| concurrent_refunds_not_supported | The refund transaction for this specific partnerTxID is still being processed. |
| invalid_merchant                 | The merchant_id passed in the request is not a valid one. Ensure that you pass your assigned merchant_id. If you are still facing issues, please reach out to our support team to retrieve your designated merchant_id for GrabPay transactions. |
| payment_not_found                | The `originTxID` specified in the request does not belong to any specific payment that is ready for a refund. |
| client_error                     | There are some errors in processing this request due to certain parameters sent in the request. |

# Check Refund Status

Check the refund status. Make sure to provide the transaction ID from the refund API endpoint.

<img src="data:image/png;base64,">


| Method        | URL|
| ---------------- | ---------- |
| GET |https://{{api-endpoint}}/grabpay/partner/v2/refund/{partnerTxID}/status?currency={currency}|



### Header Parameters

> Sample API Request

```shell
  curl -X GET
https://partner-api.stg-myteksi.com/grabpay/partner/v2/refund/{partnerTx
ID}/status?currency=SGD \
-H 'Authorization: Bearer {{ OAuth2_token }}' \
-H 'X-GID-AUX-POP: {{ POP_signature }}'
-H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
-H 'Date: Thu, 13 Sep 2018 08:49:37 GMT' \

```

| Parameter        | Type|  Description |
| ---------------- | ---------- | ---------- |
| Authorization | bearer token | **Required**​. Header required for authorization purpose. Specify the bearer access token in the Authorization header along with the Bearer authentication scheme. For example, `'Authorization: Bearer {access_token}'`.|
| X-GID-AUX-POP  | token | **Required**​. The HMAC signature computed using the OAuth access token.|
| Date | date | **Required**​.  ​The date and time in GMT format. For example, `Mon, 21 Dec 2020 08:29:58 GMT`.|
| Content-Type  | string | **Required**​.  ​ The content type of the request body. You must use `application/json` for this header because GrabPay does not currently support other formats.|
| partnerTxID  | string (max length = 32)<br/>Allowed characters:<ul><li>alphanumeric</li><li>dashes</li><li>underscores</li></ul> | **Required**​.  ​ Specify the partner transaction ID (partnerTxID) that you used when you initiated the refund.|
| currency  | Three letter ISO currency code | **Required**​. Currency that is associated with the payment amount. Specify the three-letter ISO currency code. Currently, supports only `SGD`, `MYR`, `PHP`, and `IDR`.|

# Transaction Status for Refunds

| txStatus        | Description |
| ---------------- | ---------- |
| success | The refund action ended successfully. |
| failed |The refund action had failed. |
| processing | System is processing the refund transaction, wait for the webhook notification. Alternatively, you can ​run the refund check status endpoints to find out the current status of the transaction. However, do not run the API more than once every 2 minutes. |

# Reason Codes for Refunds

| Reason Code        | Description |
| ---------------- | ---------- |
| partial_refund_not_allowed    | For this particular transaction, partial refund is disabled. |
| pending_approval              | Refund request is still pending approval.                    |
| unknown                       | The reason for the current refund request could not be determined. If the txStatus of the refund attempt is `failed`, you can mark this attempt as a failure. |
| payment_not_found | Original payment is not found or not completed for the refund request. |
| partial_refund_not_allowed |Partial refund is not allowed for this transaction.|
| transaction_decline |The refund transaction has been declined by the ststem.|
| merchant_insufficient_balance | Merchant balance is insufficient. |
| exceed_payment_amount | Refund amount exceeds payment amount.|
| refunding | System is processing a refund request.|

## How to handle in-app Webview Deelink (for Merchants)

### For ioS

Refer the sample code below for iOS:

```
func webView(_ webView: WKWebView, decidePolicyFor navigationAction: WKNavigationAction, decisionHandler: @escaping (WKNavigationActionPolicy) -> Void) {
    if let url = navigationAction.request.url,
      url.scheme?.lowercased() == "grab" {
      UIApplication.shared.open(url, options: [:], completionHandler: nil)
      decisionHandler(.cancel)
    } else {
      decisionHandler(.allow)
    }
  }

```
### For ADR

Refer the sample code below for ADR:

```
class WebActivity : AppCompatActivity() {
   override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?, persistentState: PersistableBundle?) {
       super.onCreate(savedInstanceState, persistentState)
       setContentView(R.layout.activity_web)
       val webView : WebView = findViewById(R.id.web_view)
       webView.settings.javaScriptEnabled = true
       WebView.setWebContentsDebuggingEnabled(true)
       webView.webViewClient = object : WebViewClient() {
           override fun shouldOverrideUrlLoading(view: WebView?, url: String): Boolean {
               val scheme = url.toUri().scheme
               return if (scheme == "http" || scheme == "https") {
                   false
               }
               else {
                   try {
                       startActivity(Intent(Intent.ACTION_VIEW, url.toUri()))
                   }
                   catch (exception: Exception) {
                       val playStoreUrl = "https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.grabtaxi.passenger"
                       startActivity(Intent(Intent.ACTION_VIEW, playStoreUrl.toUri()))
                       Log.e("", "exception")
                   }
                   true
               }
           }
       }
       val url = intent.extras?.getString("extras_web_url")
       if(url.isNullOrBlank()) {
           Toast.makeText(this, "Url is empty", Toast.LENGTH_LONG).show()
       }
       else
       {
           webView.loadUrl(url)
       }
   }
}

```

## Amount Details
The Amount in the GrabPay transaction is a positive integer with a currency value that the merchant accepts. The currency value follows these ISO-4217 standards:

| Country | Currency Code | Decimal | Example |
| ------- |-------------- |-------- | ------- |
| Singapore | SGD | 2 | SGD 10 = 1000 |
| Malaysia | MYR | 2 | MYR 10 = 1000 |
| Philippines | PHP | 2 | PHP 1000 = 100000 |
| Vietnam | VND | 0 | VND 10 = 10 |
| Indonesia | IDR | 2 | IDR 10000 = 1000000 |

## Troubleshooting

Here are the list of errors that you may encounter during the integration process.


**OAuth 2.0 Error Codes**

Here are the possible OAuth 2.0 error codes that you may encounter in case of issues with user’s Grab ID authentication:

| Error String    | Description|
| ---------------- | ---------- |
| invalid_request | The request is missing a required parameter, includes an invalid parameter value, includes a parameter more than once, or is otherwise malformed. |
| unauthorized_client | The client is not authorized to request an authorization code using this method. |
| access_denied | The resource owner or authorization server denied the request.|
| unsupported_response_type | The authorization server does not support obtaining an authorization code using this method.|
| invalid_scope | The requested scope is invalid, unknown, or malformed.|
| server_error | The authorization server encountered an unexpected condition that prevented it from fulfilling the request. (This error code is needed because a 500 Internal Server Error HTTP status code cannot be returned to the client via an HTTP redirect.)|
| temporarily_unavailable | The authorization server is currently unable to handle the request due to a temporary overloading or maintenance of the server. (This error code is needed because a 503 Service Unavailable HTTP status code cannot be returned to the client via an HTTP redirect.)|

**openID Connect Errors**

Here are the possible OpenID connect errors that you may encounter in case of issues with the user’s Grab ID authentication:

| Error String    | Description|
| ---------------- | ---------- |
| interaction_required | The Authorization Server requires some form for end-user interaction to proceed. This error may be returned when the prompt parameter value in the Authentication Request is ‘none’, but the Authentication Request cannot be completed without displaying a user interface for end-user interaction. |
| login_required | The Authorization Server requires end-user authentication. This error may be returned when the prompt parameter value in the Authentication Request is ‘none’, but the Authentication Request cannot be completed without displaying a user interface for end-user authentication. |
| account_selection_required | The end-user is required to select a session at the Authorization server. The end-user may be authenticated at the Authorization server with different associated accounts, but he did not select a session. This error may be returned when the ‘prompt’ parameter value in the Authentication Request is ‘none’, but the Authentication Request cannot be completed without displaying a user interface to prompt for a session to use. |
| consent_required | The Authorization Server requires end-user consent. This error may be returned when the prompt parameter value in the Authentication Request is ‘none’, but the Authentication Request cannot be completed without displaying a user interface for end-user consent.|
| invalid_request_uri | The request_uri in the Authorization Request returns an error or contains invalid data.|
| invalid_request_object | The Request parameter contains an invalid Request Object.|
| request_not_supported | The OP does not support the use of the Request parameter defined in Section 6 (​[OpenID connect 1.0 spec​](http://openid.net/specs/openid-connect-core-1_0.html#AuthError)).|
| request_uri_not_supported | The OP does not support the use of the request_uri parameter defined in Section 6 (​[OpenID connect 1.0 spec​](http://openid.net/specs/openid-connect-core-1_0.html#AuthError)).|
| registration_not_supported | The OP does not support the use of the Registration parameter defined in Section 7.2.1 (​[OpenID connect 1.0 spec​](http://openid.net/specs/openid-connect-core-1_0.html#AuthError)).|
